<br>
1 Samuel 16:7  &quot;Man looks at the outward appearance, but the Lord looks at the heart&quot;<br>
<br>
The article speaks of a lady, Lisa Bevere, the mother of three boys, who was asked to speak on an unlikely topic:  sex.<br>
<br>
Her pastor asked her to speak to a group of teenage girls about sex and, says, Bevere, the experience broke her heart.<br>
<br>
&quot;She met young women without guidance or protection who practically fed themselves to boys for affection and attention.  She saw girls who were trapped inside bodies they despised, being controlled by forces too sinister to battle.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Bevere offered a candid critique of the seductive clothing with which so many young women identify.  She encouraged the girls to ask themselves:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Do I want a guy that sees me as a conquest and has no interet in me beyond my ability to meet his sexual needs?  Or do I want someone who is intensely interested in me as a person--someone who truly loves me and wants to spend the rest of his life with me?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Reading this article brought to mind something that I've learned recently-- a current trend in high schoolers dress.<br>
<br>
My kids are still so small....but when we recently went to the High School to see the grade-schoolers Christmas program, I got to see a bit of the latest female trends, which include wearing low-cut jeans with the 'belt' of a thong showing above.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :x --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/sick.gif ALT=":x"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
1 Peter 3:3-4 &quot;Your adornment must not be merely external--braiding the hair, and wearing gold jewelry, or putting on dresses;  but let it be the hidden person of the heart, with the imperishable quality of a gentle and quiet spirit, which is precious in the sight of God&quot;<br>
<br>
In a seminar Bevere presents, she challenges girls to take a look at their wardrobes....<br>
<br>
&quot;Your enemy wants to strip you, make sport of you, and merchandise your body,&quot; she writes, &quot;but your heavenly Father wants to clothe you with beauty, strength, dignity, and honor that will endure.&quot;<br>
<br>
I bring up this article because I'd like to know your personal experiences with regards to teaching our young girls about the messages they send out by what they wear.  <br>
<br>
Or, as one with high school not so long past, what were YOUR experiences with this?  did you ever encounter peer pressure about how you dressed?<br>
<br>
